channel.description: Recent content on California Weekly Pulse

item.title: About
item.description: The California Weekly Pulse site was created and is maintained by the Stanford Data Lab. If you have any feedback, comments, or suggestions for improvements to this site, please email us.

item.title: Alameda County
item.description: Food insufficiency Unemployment Food insufficiency In the most recent survey period that ended June 16, an estimated 10.1% of Alameda County adults, or approximately 133,000 adults, lived in households with food insufficiency. These food insufficiency estimates are based upon a model. The model uses the food insufficiency rate for the entire state and the county unemployment rates to estimate food insufficiency for each county. State-level food insufficiency data is released every week, and county-level unemployment data is release every month.

item.title: California
item.description: Overview Food insufficiency Rate over time Geography Demographics Reasons Severity Free groceries or meals Unemployment Rate over time Geography Overview The data on this site is derived from the U.S. Census Bureau Household Pulse Survey (HPS) and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Local Area Unemployment Statistics (LAUS). New HPS data is released once a week, and new LAUS data is released once a month.
